+
+# User Management System Plan
+
+## Current State
+
+The platform currently has:
+
+- **Auth API** (`auth/src/`): signin/signup/me + org-switch only. No user CRUD, no role management API.
+- **DB**: `users` table has no `user_type` column. `roles` table exists with `organization_id` (nullable) but has no CRUD API. `organization_members` has a plain `role VARCHAR` column.
+- **Frontend**: 8 pages. Admin nav item is a `#` placeholder. No user management UI at all.
+- **Prisma**: only used for seeding — the real auth service uses raw `pg` SQL.
+
+## Architecture
+
+```mermaid
+flowchart TD
+    SuperAdmin["Super Admin\nuser_type = super_admin"]
+    OrgAdmin["Org Admin\nuser_type = org_admin"]
+    OrgUser["Org User\nuser_type = user"]
+
+    SuperAdmin -->|manages| SuperAdminScreens["Super Admin Screens\n/admin/super-admins"]
+    SuperAdmin -->|manages| OrgAdminScreens["Org Admin Screens\n/admin/org-admins"]
+    SuperAdmin -->|manages| AllUsers["All Users View\n/admin/users"]
+    OrgAdmin -->|manages| OrgUserScreens["Org User Screens\n/users"]
+    OrgAdmin -->|manages| RoleScreens["Custom Roles\n/roles"]
+    OrgUser -->|self-service| Profile["Profile only"]
+```
+
+
+
+## Three User Types
+
+- `super_admin` — global, no org scope, manages everything. **Created only by another super admin** (never via public signup).
+- `org_admin` — org-scoped, manages users + custom roles within their org. **Created on signup** — every new signup auto-creates an organization and assigns the registrant as `org_admin` of it.
+- `user` — regular member of an org. **Created/invited only by an org admin** — cannot self-register.
+
+Custom roles (HR, Accountant, Sales, etc.) are defined per-org and stored in the existing `roles` table (with `organization_id`). They are separate from user types.
+
+### RBAC and user_type — how they work together
+
+The platform uses **two complementary layers**:
+
+
+| Layer                                                              | What it controls                                                                                         | Where stored                   |
+| ------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
+| `user_type` on `users` table                                       | System-level access tier (`super_admin`, `org_admin`, `user`)                                            | `users.user_type` column (new) |
+| RBAC (`roles` + `permissions` + `role_permissions` + `user_roles`) | Fine-grained feature permissions (`members:create`, `documents:view`, etc.) and org-defined custom roles | Existing DB tables             |
+
+
+- `user_type` is used for **screen-level access** (who sees which admin section) and coarse API guards (`requireSuperAdmin`, `requireOrgAdmin`).
+- RBAC roles are used for **feature-level permissions** within an org — org admins define roles like HR or Sales, attach permissions to them, and assign them to users.
+- A `user` with an `HR` RBAC role still has `user_type = 'user'`; they gain HR-specific feature permissions but cannot access admin screens.
+- An `org_admin` always has the system `org_admin` RBAC role assigned by default at signup, which carries the full set of org permissions.
+
+### Signup Flow (updated)
+
+```mermaid
+sequenceDiagram
+    participant Browser
+    participant AuthAPI
+    participant DB
+
+    Browser->>AuthAPI: POST /auth/signup (name, email, password, orgName)
+    AuthAPI->>DB: INSERT users (user_type = 'org_admin')
+    AuthAPI->>DB: INSERT organizations (name = orgName, slug = auto)
+    AuthAPI->>DB: INSERT organization_members (role = 'org_admin')
+    AuthAPI->>DB: INSERT user_roles (system org_admin RBAC role)
+    AuthAPI-->>Browser: tokens + org context
+```
+
+
+
+- Signup form gains an **Organization Name** field (required).
+- `user_type` is hardcoded to `tenant_admin` in the signup controller — users cannot choose their type.
+- The org is auto-created using the provided org name; slug is derived from it.
+
+---
+
+## 1. Database Migration (new file)
+
+**File:** `infrastructure/database/migrations/011_user_type_and_management.sql`
+
+- Add `user_type` enum column to `users` table:
+
+```sql
+  ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN user_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'user'
+    CHECK (user_type IN ('super_admin', 'org_admin', 'user'));
+  
+
+```
+
+- Backfill existing super_admin/tenant_admin rows from `user_roles` → `roles` join.
+- Update JWT payload interface to include `user_type`.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Backend — Auth Service
+
+### New middleware
+
+**File:** `auth/src/middleware/permission.middleware.ts` (extend existing)
+
+- `requireSuperAdmin` — checks `user.user_type === 'super_admin'`
+- `requireOrgAdmin` — checks `user.user_type` is `super_admin` or `org_admin`
+
+### New controllers
+
+
+| File                                                 | Purpose                                              |
+| ---------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
+| `auth/src/controllers/user-admin.controller.ts`      | CRUD for super admins, org admins, org users         |
+| `auth/src/controllers/role-management.controller.ts` | CRUD for custom tenant roles + permission assignment |
+
+
+**Super Admin controller actions:**
+
+- `listSuperAdmins`, `createSuperAdmin`, `updateSuperAdmin`, `deleteSuperAdmin`
+- `listOrgAdmins`, `createOrgAdmin`, `updateOrgAdmin`, `deleteOrgAdmin`
+- `listAllUsers` (global view)
+
+**Org Admin controller actions:**
+
+- `listOrgUsers`, `createOrgUser`, `updateOrgUser`, `deleteOrgUser`
+- `assignUserRole`, `removeUserRole`
+
+**Role management actions:**
+
+- `listRoles`, `createRole`, `updateRole`, `deleteRole` (org-scoped)
+- `listPermissions` (reference list for building roles)
+
+### New routes
+
+**File:** `auth/src/routes/user-admin.routes.ts`
+
+```
+POST   /api/admin/super-admins          requireSuperAdmin
+GET    /api/admin/super-admins          requireSuperAdmin
+PUT    /api/admin/super-admins/:id      requireSuperAdmin
+DELETE /api/admin/super-admins/:id      requireSuperAdmin
+
+GET    /api/admin/org-admins            requireSuperAdmin
+POST   /api/admin/org-admins            requireSuperAdmin
+PUT    /api/admin/org-admins/:id        requireSuperAdmin
+DELETE /api/admin/org-admins/:id        requireSuperAdmin
+
+GET    /api/admin/users                 requireSuperAdmin
+```
+
+**File:** `auth/src/routes/org-users.routes.ts`
+
+```
+GET    /api/organizations/:orgId/users          requireOrgAdmin
+POST   /api/organizations/:orgId/users          requireOrgAdmin
+PUT    /api/organizations/:orgId/users/:id      requireOrgAdmin
+DELETE /api/organizations/:orgId/users/:id      requireOrgAdmin
+```
+
+**File:** `auth/src/routes/role-management.routes.ts`
+
+```
+GET    /api/organizations/:orgId/roles          requireOrgAdmin
+POST   /api/organizations/:orgId/roles          requireOrgAdmin
+PUT    /api/organizations/:orgId/roles/:id      requireOrgAdmin
+DELETE /api/organizations/:orgId/roles/:id      requireOrgAdmin
+GET    /api/permissions                         requireOrgAdmin  (reference list)
+```
+
+Also update JWT generation (`auth/src/utils/jwt.ts`) to include `user_type` in the access token payload and the `/auth/me` response.
+
+### Signup controller changes (`auth/src/controllers/auth.controller.ts`)
+
+- Accept `organizationName` in the signup request body (required, validated).
+- In a single DB transaction:
+  1. Insert user with `user_type = 'org_admin'`
+  2. Insert organization (name = `organizationName`, slug = auto-generated from name)
+  3. Insert `organization_members` row linking the user as `role = 'org_admin'`
+  4. Insert `user_roles` row assigning the system `org_admin` RBAC role
+- Return tokens with `org_id` already set (user is immediately in org context post-signup).
+- Update `app/auth/signup/page.tsx` to include an **Organization Name** input field.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Frontend — New Pages
+
+All pages use the existing `apiFetch` + `localStorage` token pattern. No new auth libraries needed.
+
+### Page structure
+
+```
+frontend/app/
+├── admin/
+│   ├── super-admins/
+│   │   ├── page.tsx              ← List super admins
+│   │   ├── create/page.tsx       ← Create super admin
+│   │   └── [id]/edit/page.tsx    ← Edit super admin
+│   └── org-admins/
+│       ├── page.tsx              ← List org admins (with org filter)
+│       ├── create/page.tsx       ← Create org admin
+│       └── [id]/edit/page.tsx    ← Edit org admin
+├── users/
+│   ├── page.tsx                  ← List org users (scoped to current org)
+│   ├── create/page.tsx           ← Create/invite user
+│   └── [id]/edit/page.tsx        ← Edit user + assign role
+└── roles/
+    ├── page.tsx                  ← List custom roles
+    ├── create/page.tsx           ← Create role + assign permissions
+    └── [id]/edit/page.tsx        ← Edit role
+```
+
+### Sidebar updates
+
+**File:** `frontend/components/Layout.tsx`
+
+Replace the `Settings → #` placeholder with role-conditional nav sections:
+
+- **Super Admin only**: "Super Admins", "Org Admins" links under an "Administration" section
+- **Super Admin + Org Admin**: "Users", "Roles" links under a "User Management" section
+- All conditional on `user_type` from the `/auth/me` response (store in state alongside current user)
+
+### Route middleware protection
+
+**File:** `frontend/middleware.ts` (extend existing)
+
+- `/admin/`* routes redirect to `/dashboard` if `user_type !== 'super_admin'`
+- `/users/`* and `/roles/`* redirect if `user_type === 'user'` (only `org_admin` and `super_admin` can access)
+- Since tokens are in localStorage (client-side), use a client-side guard component for pages (server middleware can only check cookies; add a `withAdminGuard` HOC or use `useEffect` redirect pattern consistent with the current codebase).
+
+---
+
+## 4. Key Design Decisions
+
+- **user_type vs role lookup**: `user_type` is stored directly on the `users` table (fast, simple). Custom roles (HR, Accountant, etc.) remain in the `roles` table per-org — they do not change `user_type`.
+- **Super admin has no org_id**: When `user_type = 'super_admin'`, `org_id` in the JWT is `null`; super admin API routes skip the org scope check.
+- **Org-defined custom roles**: Each org admin can create roles (e.g. HR, Sales) and assign any `resource:action` permissions from the existing `permissions` table via RBAC. These are purely functional permissions — they don't change the user's `user_type`.
+- **Prisma/SQL alignment**: The auth service continues with raw `pg`. Prisma schema (`frontend/prisma/schema.prisma`) is updated to reflect the new `user_type` field for documentation/seeding purposes only.
+
